  <section id="our-work-title" class="paragraph paragraph--text paragraph-container paragraph-158906">
  <div class="article_wrapper">
    
      <center><h3>Our work</h3></center>

  </div>
</section>

  <section id="our-impact" class="slider-slice_container paragraph-container">
    <section class="text_link_carousel black title-centre" aria-labelledby="carousel-heading">
            <div class="article_wrapper text-link-heading-container">
                        <p>
            <p>Here is a snapshot of some of our projects funded by WWF-UK supporters.</p>
        </p>
              </div>
            <div class="splide">
        <div class="splide__track article_wrapper">
          <ul class="splide__list">
                                                                    <li class="splide__slide">
                <figure>
                  <img src="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=LuPA-u_E"
                       srcset="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=LuPA-u_E 320w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_640/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=8tc8KLVz 640w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_768/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=Y7q5aTwn 768w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1024/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=8-P_KnAV 1024w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1200/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=Fbd55OcD 1200w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1440/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=1JOHKjVK 1440w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1536/public/2022-04/_WW1164298.jpg?h=a7a38362&amp;itok=Z9CiB1L4 1536w"
                       alt="Backlit wildflower meadow in the golden light"
                       sizes="(max-width:768px) 95vw, 25vw"
                  />
                                      <div class="splide-copyright">© Joseph Gray / WWF-UK</div>
                                    <figcaption>
                    <h4>Restoring UK wildflower meadows</h4>
                    <div class="figure-text-container">
                      <p><p>The UK is&nbsp;one of the most nature depleted countries in the world and it urgently needs restoring. Since the 1930s, <strong>we’ve lost 97% of our lowland wildflower meadows</strong>. Not only are they home to thousands of UK native species, their grassland soil also helps in the fight against climate change by storing carbon. We’re working with our partner Air Wick to help bring these precious meadows back to life. &nbsp;From the partnership’s launch in 2021, we’re aiming to restore <strong>20 million</strong> <strong>square feet of UK wildflower habitats (approx. 185ha).</strong></p></p>
                    </div>
                  </figcaption>
                                                          <div class="find-out-more-container">
                                                              <a href="/who-we-are/who-we-work-with/botanica" class="find-out-more-btn">
                        Find out more
                      </a>
                                      </div>
                                  </figure>
              </li>
                                                                    <li class="splide__slide">
                <figure>
                  <img src="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=OEZUre4d"
                       srcset="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=OEZUre4d 320w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_640/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=vIwTMTKV 640w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_768/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=OwDOCiCy 768w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1024/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=fa56UBCB 1024w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1200/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=w_EIQN6G 1200w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1440/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=QP-4ep4g 1440w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1536/public/2022-07/_WW1206454.jpg?h=dbcb99dc&amp;itok=lvzLhQTl 1536w"
                       alt="Belén Sota, Peruvian Amazonian cattle rancher. Madre de Dios, Peru"
                       sizes="(max-width:768px) 95vw, 25vw"
                  />
                                      <div class="splide-copyright">© Pierina Bellota / WWF-Perú</div>
                                    <figcaption>
                    <h4>Regenerative Agriculture in Peru</h4>
                    <div class="figure-text-container">
                      <p><p>The Peruvian Amazon is one of the most <a>biodiverse ecosystem</a>s in the world. However, for decades it has been <a>under pressure from</a> human activities such as illegal logging, agriculture and livestock farming. With UK PACT, we are supporting ‘Farmer Field Schools’ to boost&nbsp; <strong>regenerative agriculture practices in the region</strong>, whilst working with women and young people so that the whole family can become more involved in the process. So far, WWF-Peru have <strong>assisted more than 200 livestock producers</strong> in applying regenerative agriculture practices on their farms, helping to <strong>protect and restore precious ecosystems.</strong></p></p>
                    </div>
                  </figcaption>
                                                          <div class="find-out-more-container">
                                                              <a href="https://www.wwf.org.pe/?376151%2FFarmer-Field-Schools-that-change-lives-and-restore-the-Peruvian-Amazon=" class="find-out-more-btn">
                        Find out more
                      </a>
                                      </div>
                                  </figure>
              </li>
                                                                    <li class="splide__slide">
                <figure>
                  <img src="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=CLC8pPpB"
                       srcset="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=CLC8pPpB 320w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_640/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=wF8fmuHK 640w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_768/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=vXlnjyG5 768w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1024/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=ZZGe2ooE 1024w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1200/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=KspCRlMk 1200w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1440/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=iXc1lxmF 1440w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1536/public/2022-08/Kenya.JPG?h=d5895ce4&amp;itok=3meVSqft 1536w"
                       alt="RESTORING LANDSCAPES IN KENYA"
                       sizes="(max-width:768px) 95vw, 25vw"
                  />
                                      <div class="splide-copyright">© WWF-Kenya</div>
                                    <figcaption>
                    <h4>Restoring landscapes in Kenya</h4>
                    <div class="figure-text-container">
                      <p><p>Kaptagat forest block, part of the Elgeyo Hills-Cherangany Ecosystem in Kenya, covers over 19,000 hectares. This area is home to eight different communities that rely on the region for water and agriculture. The landscape also <strong>supports the area’s rich plant and animal life,</strong> but this special place is under threat. Unsustainable use of the land means <strong>forest and grassland areas are declining at an alarming rate</strong>. We’re working with partners to<strong> implement a restoration plan</strong>, including agroforestry, restoration of degraded soils, building capacity and upscaling indigenous seedling production by the local community.</p></p>
                    </div>
                  </figcaption>
                                                          <div class="find-out-more-container">
                                                              <a href="https://www.wwfkenya.org/?233450%2FUK-PACT-Greening-Kaptagat-Project-Launched=" class="find-out-more-btn">
                        Find out more
                      </a>
                                      </div>
                                  </figure>
              </li>
                                                                    <li class="splide__slide">
                <figure>
                  <img src="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=kt54g3YY"
                       srcset="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=kt54g3YY 320w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_640/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=DxypyU6- 640w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_768/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=H0Tn9XBy 768w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1024/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=Ya4YsaDY 1024w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1200/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=Mgzyytlw 1200w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1440/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=KFDCPt8_ 1440w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1536/public/2022-08/_WW2129433.jpg?h=82f92a78&amp;itok=AsUoTVVn 1536w"
                       alt="Seagrass"
                       sizes="(max-width:768px) 95vw, 25vw"
                  />
                                      <div class="splide-copyright">© Lewis Jefferies / WWF-UK</div>
                                    <figcaption>
                    <h4>Restoring seagrass beds</h4>
                    <div class="figure-text-container">
                      <p><p>Over the last century, we’ve lost up to 92% of our seagrass meadows from our UK seas. And they continue to decline globally at a rate of 7% per year.&nbsp;With your support, we’re turning the tide. Together with partners through our Seagrass Ocean Rescue Programme, we are collecting and planting <strong>over 5 million </strong>seeds to restore seagrass meadows around Anglesey and the Llŷn Peninsula in Wales, the Solent in England and the Firth of Forth in Scotland.&nbsp;Seagrass is vital to our oceans and a key player in bringing our world back to life. It provides <strong>habitats for sealife,</strong> and despite accounting for less than 0.1% of the worlds oceans, they sequester around 10% of the carbon buried in ocean sediment every year.&nbsp;Per hectare, <strong>seagrasses can store twice as much carbon than terrestrial forests</strong> – helping to counteract climate change.</p></p>
                    </div>
                  </figcaption>
                                                          <div class="find-out-more-container">
                                                              <a href="/what-we-do/planting-hope-how-seagrass-can-tackle-climate-change" class="find-out-more-btn">
                        Find out more
                      </a>
                                      </div>
                                  </figure>
              </li>
                                                                    <li class="splide__slide">
                <figure>
                  <img src="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=YPRLR1GX"
                       srcset="https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_320/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=YPRLR1GX 320w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_640/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=seoE-6_2 640w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_768/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=uD8l8NRS 768w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1024/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=6SR-fVQY 1024w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1200/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=mRASl-3B 1200w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1440/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=I3uBDroi 1440w,
                           https://www.wwf.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/text_link_carousel_slider_1536/public/2021-03/Large_WW2122808.jpg?h=3e43625b&amp;itok=QvguVWuw 1536w"
                       alt=" A tiger in Bardia National Park, Nepal. Image made with a camera trap."
                       sizes="(max-width:768px) 95vw, 25vw"
                  />
                                      <div class="splide-copyright">© Emmanuel Rondeau / WWF-US</div>
                                    <figcaption>
                    <h4>Protecting key tiger habitats</h4>
                    <div class="figure-text-container">
                      <p><p>Tigers are the most threatened big cat species globally, reduced to around 5% of their historic range. Tigers play a key role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem and the vast areas of forest they need are a vital carbon store. WWF works with Governments, local communities and other conservation organisations to help <strong>crack down on the illegal wildlife trade</strong>, and <strong>protect key tiger habitats and corridors</strong>. WWF-Nepal played a key part in delivering the National Tiger and Prey Survey 2022, which covered 18,928 sq. km - over 12 per cent of Nepal. The survey confirmed <strong>Nepal had more than doubled its number of wild tigers to an estimate of 355 between 2009-2022</strong>, indicating the effectiveness of these collective conservation efforts.</p></p>
                    </div>
                  </figcaption>
                                                          <div class="find-out-more-container">
                                                              <a href="https://www.wwf.org.uk/press-release/tigers-roar-back" class="find-out-more-btn">
                        Find out more
                      </a>
                                      </div>
                                  </figure>
              </li>
                      </ul>
        </div>
